[5] Cholera - Zambia
Date: Fri 1 Sep 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Int. Fed of Red Cross And Red Crescent Societies (IFRC) [edited]
<http://www.reliefweb.int/rw/RWB.NSF/db900SID/LSGZ-6T8JMQ?OpenDocument>

[Period covered by this Interim Report: 14 Jan to 12 May 2006]
Cholera outbreaks occur annually in Zambia mainly due to poor
settlement planning in both urban and rural areas, resulting in
limited availability and access to basic services, such as clean and
safe water supply, improved sanitation as well as waste disposal
facilities. Just 4 months after the 2004- 2005 epidemic, the country
started recording new cholera cases in August 2005.
Between 13 Aug 2005 and 31 Jan 2006, a total of 2415 confirmed and
suspected cases, with 21 deaths (10 died at cholera centers and 11
were brought in dead) were reported. By 5 Apr 2006, the total cases
stood at 7615, of which 5991 cases were recorded in Lusaka District
alone. By 7 Mar 2006, the outbreak had affected 6 other provinces as
follows: Central Province (443 cases), Copper Belt Province (233
cases), Eastern Province (221 cases), Luapula Province (31 cases),
North-Western Province (2 cases) and Southern Province (314 cases).
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[A map of Zambia showing the provinces can be found at:
<http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/zambia.pdf>.
